04604nam a22006495i 9780520974739DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019044983  a97805209747397 a10.1525/97805209747392doi  a(DE-B1597)551378  a(OCoLC)1120693598  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHD9536.G52 4aHD9536.G52bC69 2020 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a338.2/741096672231 aCoyle Rosen, Lauren, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFires of Gold :bLaw, Spirit, and Sacrificial Labor in Ghana /cLauren Coyle Rosen. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAtelier: Ethnographic Inquiry in the Twenty-First Century ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMaps -- tIntroduction -- t1. Artisanal Miners and Sacrificial Laws -- t2. Spiritual Sovereigns in the Shadows -- t3. Pray for the Mine -- t4. Fallen Chiefs and Divine Violence -- t5. Effigies, Strikes, and Courts -- tConclusion: Out of the Golden Twilight? -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFires of Gold is a powerful ethnography of the often shrouded cultural, legal, political, and spiritual forces governing the gold mining industry in Ghana, one of Africa's most celebrated democracies. Lauren Coyle Rosen argues that significant sources of power have arisen outside of the formal legal system to police, adjudicate, and navigate conflict in this theater of violence, destruction, and rebirth. These authorities, or shadow sovereigns, include the transnational mining company, collectivized artisanal miners, civil society advocacy groups, and significant religious figures and spiritual forces from African, Islamic, and Christian traditions. Often more salient than official bodies of government, the shadow sovereigns reveal a reconstitution of sovereign power-one that, in many ways, is generated by hidden dimensions of the legal system. Coyle Rosen also contends that spiritual forces are central in anchoring and animating shadow sovereigns as well as key forms of legal authority, economic value, and political contestation. This innovative book illuminates how the crucible of gold, itself governed by spirits, serves as a critical site for embodied struggles over the realignment of the classical philosophical triad: the city, the soul, and the sacred.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEthnologyzGhanaxReligious aspects. 0aGold mines and miningxPolitical aspectszGhana. 0aGold mines and miningzGhanaxReligious aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069041540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520974739zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520974739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520974739.jpg  a978-3-11-069041-5  UC Press Frontlist eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070472-3  EBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DGGb2020  aZDB-23-SEWb2020